iChoose the Right OS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- macOS is optimized for Apple hardware; Windows isn't. Tests show		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMacbook CPU temperatures run 5°C higher in Windows than Linux when		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iidle (only desktop + temperature tool running).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, Windows may be better for Flash content—macOS has poor Flash		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isupport, causing high CPU usage and extra heat.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iReduce Background Processes		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Background apps like Dropbox or idle Xunlei consume CPU resources,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
igenerating heat. Close them when unused; launch only when needed.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLower Ambient Temperature		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Server rooms blast AC to 20°C in summer because powerhouse CPUs like		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iXeon E3/E5/E7 generate extreme heat. Poor cooling leads to reduced		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilifespan, crashes, or worse... egg-frying scenarios.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt home, using your Macbook in an AC-cooled room typically lowers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itemperatures by 5–10°C vs. non-AC environments.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Winter heating doesn’t count here.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
